    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but I'm still finding the \"non-local\" part hard to wrap my head around. Einstein famously called it \"spooky action at a distance,\" right? What did he mean by that \"spooky\" part specifically in relation to how these particles act?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein's \"spooky action at a distance\" refers to the idea that entangled particles can affect each other instantaneously, regardless of the distance between them. It's as if the state of one particle is \"tied\" to the other, and changing the state of one particle instantly affects the other, even if they're separated by vast distances. This seems to violate the classical notion of space and time, where information would have to travel at the speed of light for any effect to be observed. Think of it like a \"hidden connection\" that lets the particles \"talk\" to each other in a way that bypasses space and time.",
      "source": "target",
